l</route>   <title>Filippo Sestini</title> <meta name="position">PhD Student</meta><meta name="institution">University of Nottingham</meta><meta name="external">http://www.cs.nott.ac.uk/~psxfs5/</meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0002-8701-5613</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>17244</anchor> <rss>loïcpujet.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>loïcpujet</addr>  <route>loïcpujet.xml</route>   <title>Loïc Pujet</title> <meta name="external">https://pujet.fr/</meta><meta name="institution">Stockholm University</meta><meta name="position">Sverker Lerheden Postdoctoral Fellow</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>17245</anchor> <rss>yueniu.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>yueniu</addr>  <route>yueniu.xml</route>   <title>Yue Niu</title> <meta name="position">PhD Student</meta><meta name="phd-advisor">robertharper</meta><meta name="institution">Carnegie Mellon University</meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0003-4888-6042</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>PhD student of <link href="robertharper.xml" type="local" title="Robert Harper">Robert Harper</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>17246</anchor> <rss>sterling-2022-pujet-workshop.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>sterling-2022-pujet-workshop</addr>  <route>sterling-2022-pujet-workshop.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>14</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Controlling unfolding in type theory</title> <meta name="slides">https://www.jonmsterling.com/slides/sterling-2022-pujet-workshop.pdf</meta><meta name="venue">Workshop on Dependent Type Theory (to celebrate the Defense of <link href="loïcpujet.xml" type="local" title="Loïc Pujet">Loïc Pujet</link>)</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We present a novel mechanism for controlling the unfolding of definitions in dependent type theory. Traditionally, proof assistants let users specify whether each definition can or cannot be unfolded in the remainder of a development; unfolding definitions is often necessary in order to reason about them, but an excess of unfolding can result in brittle proofs and intractably large proof goals. In our system, definitions are by default not unfolded, but users can selectively unfold them in a local manner. We justify our mechanism by means of elaboration to a core type theory with <em>extension types</em>, a connective first introduced in the context of homotopy type theory.  We prove a normalization theorem for our core calculus and have implemented our system in the cooltt proof assistant, providing both theoretical and practical evidence for it.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>